	<span class="csC2FEE544">ESSION</span></p><p class="cs709C557D"><span class="csC2FEE544">Introduced</span></p><p class="cs3E63B65"><span class="cs8498B7A6">House Bill 4459</span></p><p class="csFF933113"><span class="csADC6E5DB">By Delegates Heckert, Amos, Flanigan, Jennings, Chiarelli, Hillenbrand, Hott, McCormick, Funkhouser, and Fehrenbacher</span></p><p class="cs8BEF69CE"><span class="cs7B75DFFE">[Introduced January 16, 2026; referred to the Committee on Health and Human Resources then the Judiciary]</span></p><p class="cs29F66C3F"><span class="csEF05ACC">A BILL to repeal &sect;19-12F-1, &sect;19-12F-2, &sect;19-12F-3, &sect;19-12F-4, &sect;19-12F-5, &sect;19-12F-6, &sect;19-12F-7, &sect;19-12F-8, &sect;19-12F-9, &nbsp;&sect;19-12F-9a, &sect;19-12F-10, and &sect;19-12F-11 of the Code of West Virginia, 1931, as amended; and to amend &sect;60-10-1, &sect;60-10-2, and &sect;60A-2-204 of said code, relating to classifying kratom and its components as Schedule I controlled substances. </span></p><p class="cs63FD752D"><span class="cs93AB6E8B">Be it enacted by the Legislature of West Virginia:</span></p><p class="cs63FD752D"><span class="cs93AB6E8B">&nbsp;</span></p><h1 class="cs709C557D">
